===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|chivalrie}}, a late 13th century loan from {{etyl|fro|en}} word {{m|fro|chevalerie}}, "knighthood, chivalry, nobility, cavalry" (11th century), the ''[[-erie]]'' abstract of {{m|fro|chevaler}} "knight, horseman", from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|caballarius||horseman, knight}}, a derivation from {{m|la|caballus||horse}}.
{{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|caballaria||knighthood, status or fief of a knight}} dates to the 12th century.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈʃɪvalri/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|chivalries}}

# {{label|en|now|_|rare|historical}} [[cavalry|Cavalry]]; horsemen armed for battle.
#* '''1999''', {{w|George RR Martin}}, ''A Clash of Kings'', Bantam 2011, p. 529:
#*: ‘Most of the lords who rode with Lord Renly to Storm's End have gone over banner-and-blade to Stannis, with all their '''chivalry'''.’
# {{label|en|obsolete}} The fact or condition of being a [[knight]]; knightly skill, prowess.
# The ethical code of the [[knight]] prevalent in Medieval [[Europe]], having such primary virtues as [[mercy]] towards the poor and oppressed, [[humility]], [[honour]], [[sacrifice]], fear of [[God]], [[faithfulness]], [[courage]] and utmost [[graciousness]] and [[courtesy]] to ladies.
# Courtesy, respect and honourable conduct between opponents in wartime.
# Courteous behaviour, especially that of men towards women.
# {{label|en|UK|legal|historical}} A [[tenure]] of [[land]]s by knightly service.

